        <p>Traveling alone with your kids is completely doable — millions of single parents do it every year. What trips people up is the stuff nobody warns you about: the consent letter you didn't know you needed, the custody clause about out-of-state travel, the security line with a stroller and two bags. Sort these once and the rest is just a vacation.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>Start here if you share custody:</strong> check your custody order <em>before</em> you book. Many agreements restrict out-of-state or international travel, require notifying the other parent, or set notice periods. Booking first and reading later is how trips get cancelled.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>The travel-consent letter</h2>
        <p>When one parent travels with a child, border agents, airlines (especially international), and sometimes domestic authorities may ask for a <strong>consent letter</strong> from the other parent — proof you're allowed to travel with your own kid. It's not always required, but not having one when it <em>is</em> asked for can end a trip at the gate.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>What it includes:</strong> the child's details, both parents' details, the trip dates and destination, and the other parent's signed permission. Notarized is strongest, especially for international travel.</li>
          <li><strong>Carry it even for domestic trips</strong> if you have a different last name than your child, or if your custody situation is contentious.</li>
          <li><strong>For international travel,</strong> review the official guidance on the <a href="https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/passports/need-passport/under-16.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">U.S. State Department site</a> — minors have their own passport and consent rules, and both parents typically must consent to a child's passport.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What to carry</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>The consent letter</strong> (notarized for international).</li>
          <li><strong>A copy of your custody order</strong> — the relevant page about travel.</li>
          <li><strong>The child's ID or passport,</strong> plus a copy of their birth certificate for international trips.</li>
          <li><strong>Emergency contacts and any medical info</strong> — allergies, medications, your pediatrician's number.</li>
          <li><strong>Travel insurance details</strong> if you bought a policy — see below.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Getting through the airport solo</h2>
        <p>One adult, multiple kids, and a security line is the moment most dads dread. It's smoother than it looks with a little prep.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>TSA lets you carry kids' liquids, formula, and snacks</strong> over the usual limit — just declare them. Kids under 12 generally keep shoes on.</li>
          <li><strong>Wear your bags, not your hands.</strong> A backpack each leaves your hands free for kids and documents.</li>
          <li><strong>Gate-check the stroller</strong> — use it right up to the plane door, then it's waiting for you on arrival.</li>
          <li><strong>Tell the airline you're traveling with kids</strong> when you book; many will seat you together and some offer family boarding.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Travel insurance</h2>
        <p>When you're the only adult, a single hiccup — a sick kid, a cancelled flight, lost bags — lands entirely on you. A basic travel-insurance policy covers trip cancellation, medical costs, and delays, and it's cheap relative to a non-refundable trip.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Worth it for:</strong> expensive non-refundable trips, international travel, and anything during cold-and-flu season.</li>
          <li><strong>Check what you already have</strong> — some rewards cards include trip protection if you book on them.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><a class="platform-cta" href="{{ '/go/travel-insurance' | url }}" rel="sponsored nofollow">Compare travel insurance →</a></p>

        <h2>On the trip itself</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Lower the bar.</strong> One or two things a day, not a packed schedule. You're the only one who can adjust, so leave slack.</li>
          <li><strong>Build in downtime.</strong> A pool afternoon resets everyone, including you.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep a routine anchor</strong> — same-ish bedtime, a familiar snack, a comfort item from home. It prevents the over-tired spiral.</li>
          <li><strong>Take the photo, then put the phone away.</strong> They'll remember that you were there, not what you captured.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>You've got this.</strong> The first solo trip is the hardest because it's unknown. After one, you'll have a system — and a kid who can't wait for the next one.</p>
        </div>

